Unpublished Opinion No. 2004-UP-166
Submitted January 29, 2004 â€“ Filed March 15, 2004

VACATED


  
    
      
Chief Attorney Daniel T. Stacey, SC Office of Appellate Defense, 
  of Columbia, for Appellant.
Attorney General Charles M. Condon, Chief Deputy Attorney 
  General John W. McIntosh, Assistant Attorney General W. Rutledge Martin, all 
  of Columbia; and Solicitor Thomas E. Pope, of York, for Respondent.
      
    
  



 PER CURIAM:Â  Barry Barrentine 
  appeals his conviction and sentence for second-degree criminal sexual conduct 
  with a minor. Â It resulted from a guilty plea upon an indictment that 
  charged him with first-degree criminal sexual conduct with a minor, allegedly 
  a seven-year-old female.Â  Barrentine contends the trial court lacked jurisdiction 
  to accept that plea because second-degree criminal sexual conduct with a minor 
  [1]  is not a lesser-included offense of first-degree criminal sexual 
  conduct with a minor. [2] Â We agree. [3] Â  
  Cohen v. State, 354 S.C. 563, 582 S.E.2d 403 (2003).
VACATED.
GOOLSBY, HOWARD, and KITTREDGE, JJ., 
  concur.

 
   [1]  S.C. Code Ann. Â§ 16-3-655(2) (2003) 
    defines second-degree criminal sexual conduct with a minor as a â€œsexual battery 
    with a victim who is fourteen years of age or less but who is at least eleven 
    years of age.â€

 
    [2]    S.C. Code Ann. Â§ 16-3-655(1) (2003) 
    defines first-degree criminal sexual conduct with a minor as a â€œsexual battery 
    with [a] victim who is less than eleven years of age.â€

 
    [3]    We decide this case without oral argument 
    pursuant to Rule 215, SCACR.






